    "title": "Fragments of Consciousness",
    "link": "https://palakmathur.substack.com/p/fragments-of-consciousness",
    "content": "Dr. Geeta Sharma stepped into the quantum liquid conduit (QLC) chamber at her Dallas lab, her bindi glowing faintly under the sterile light. She had invented the QLC technology, the crown jewel of modern travel. Yet, as the liquid swirled around her, flushing her into the quantum stream, a minor ripple of unease gripped her. The transit took seconds. When she emerged at the Flush Port in Delhi, applause greeted her. She smiled, but something was wrong. Her shadow lagged behind her, moving moments after she did. Reflections in chrome surfaces flickered, her face distorted like an unfinished painting. Thanks for reading Vichar Vahak - Stories and Musings! Subscribe for free to receive new posts and support my work. By the second day, memories began slipping away. Her grandfather\u2019s wisdom of Yoga Sutras - gone. Her first Diwali sparkler - fading. Whispers tugged at her mind, Sanskrit chants echoing through her thoughts. Desperate, she flushed herself back into the quantum liquid conduit chamber with a stabilizer prototype, descending into a glowing, shifting cosmos. There she found herself - minor fragments of her consciousness scattered like broken mirrors. One fragment, cold and calculating, recoiled at her emotions. Another, a frightened child, clung to fading memories. The final fragment loomed: a twisted version of herself, eyes blazing with rage. \u201cYou left me behind,\u201d it hissed. Geeta closed her eyes, recalling her grandfather\u2019s teaching: \u201cTo find balance, embrace every part of yourself.\u201d She stretched out her hand. When she emerged from the conduit again, her shadow moved in perfect harmony. Yet, in the glass chamber of her lab, her reflection lingered a moment too long. Generate an image in oil colors showing fragments of consciousness Note: This story was written as part of 250-words micro-fiction challenge by NYC MIDNIGHT and received Honorable Mention in the second round. The genre was Science Fiction, action was flushing the toilet, and the word was minor. Thanks for reading Vichar Vahak - Stories and Musings! Subscribe for free to receive new posts and support my work.",
